    &lt;Title&gt;Care and Compassion in the CCU&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;On Thursday 7th March I accompanied my neighbour to the CCU where his wife had been admitted the previous week.
The doctor had the difficult job of telling my neighbour that his wife was suffering from total organ failure, and there was nothing that could be done to help the situation.
Quite frankly, I was full of admiration for this doctor, who delivered the bad news in the most caring, sensitive and compassionate way whilst still giving a detailed and comprehensive account about the problems my neighbourâ€™s wife had, and explaining why a non-invasive treatment plan had been decided upon.
The next day my neighbour was telephoned and asked to attend the hospital.  When we arrived, we were taken into a side room, and told that his wife had died that morning.  The nurse who delivered the sad news was compassionate, supportive, thoughtful and offered him all the help he needed.
It is difficult to ease the pain of losing someone, but the hospital should be proud of not only the two people I have mentioned, but all the team who came into contact with my neighbour and his wife, for displaying their professional yet compassionate responses in a difficult situation.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
